Preparation of AlCl3-CDs: Take 0.6 g of oPD and 0.01786 g of AlCl3·6H2O and fully dissolve them in 30 mL of anhydrous ethanol. The solution was then placed in a 50 mL Teflon reactor and reacted in an oven at a high temperature of 200 ℃ for 12h. After the reaction was completed, it was naturally cooled to room temperature, and the obtained crude product emitted bright red under a 365 nm UV lamp. After separation and purification of the product by silica gel column chromatography (ethanol as the eluent), red emission and a small amount of yellow emission CDs could be obtained (the PL emission spectra and normalized UV–vis absorption, Ex, and Em spectra are shown in 
                           Fig. S1
                        ). Finally, CD powders were obtained by rotary evaporation and vacuum drying. The mass of red CDs (AlCl3-CDs) was 0.37 g, and the yellow CDs was 0.017 g. Therefore, according to the equation Xr =XC·S, we can calculate the conversion rate of red CDs as 61.7% (where Xr represents the conversion rate of red CDs, XC represents the conversion rate of CDs, and S represents the mass proportion of red CDs to total CDs).

Preparation of CuCl2-CDs: 0.6 g of oPD and 0.0036 g of CuCl2·2H2O were fully dissolved in 30 mL of anhydrous ethanol, and the solution was poured into a 50 mL Teflon reactor and then placed in an oven at 200 ℃ for 12h. After the reaction was completed and cooled to room temperature, the obtained crude product was orange-emitting under a 365 nm UV lamp. Then the product was separated by silica gel column chromatography (ethanol as the eluent) to obtain red, yellow, and green emission CDs (the PL emission spectra and normalized UV–vis absorption, Ex, and Em spectra are shown in 
                           Fig. S2
                        ). Finally, CD powders were obtained by rotary evaporation and vacuum drying. The mass of red CDs (CuCl2-CDs) was 0.071 g, the yellow and green CDs were 0.21 and 0.057 g, respectively. Therefore, according to the equation Xr =XC·S, we can calculate the conversion rate of red CDs as 11.8%.

Preparation of FeCl3-CDs: 0.6 g oPD and 0.0083 g FeCl3·6H2O were dissolved in 30 mL anhydrous ethanol, then placed in a 50 mL Teflon reactor, and heated in an oven at 200 ℃ for 12h. After the reaction was completed, it was cooled to room temperature naturally, and the crude product emitted orange under a 365 nm UV lamp. The product was then separated by silica gel column chromatography (ethanol as the eluent) to obtain red and yellow emission CDs (the PL emission spectra and normalized UV–vis absorption, Ex, and Em spectra are shown in 
                           Fig. S3
                        ). Finally, CD powders were obtained by rotary evaporation and vacuum drying. The mass of red CDs (FeCl3-CDs) was 0.061 g and the yellow CDs was 0.26 g. Therefore, according to the equation Xr =XC·S, we can calculate the conversion rate of red CDs as 10.2%.

Control Experiment 1: 0.6 g oPD was fully dissolved in 30 mL anhydrous ethanol, then poured into a 50 mL Teflon reactor, and placed in an oven at 200 ℃ for 12h. After the reaction, it was naturally cooled to room temperature, and the crude product was emitted yellow-green under a 365 nm UV lamp. The product was then separated by silica gel column chromatography (ethanol as the eluent), and green, yellow, and a very small amount of red emission CDs were obtained (the PL emission spectra and normalized UV–vis absorption, Ex, and Em spectra are shown in 
                           Fig. S4
                        ). Since the amount of red CDs is very small and difficult to collect, the conversion rate of red CDs was less than 1%.

Since AlCl3-CDs have red fluorescence with a high PLQY value of 29.99%, we explore their potential applications as fluorescent bioimaging agents. First, we chose the CCK8 assay to evaluate the cytotoxicity of AlCl3-CDs on HeLa cells [45]. According to the analysis of the test results, the cell viability was close to 90% after incubation at 50 μg/mL for 24 h without light (
                        Fig. S11
                     ), indicating that AlCl3-CDs have low cytotoxicity and good biocompatibility for HeLa cells. Subsequently, 50 μg/mL AlCl3-CDs were stained with HeLa cells to explore their fluorescence bioimaging capabilities. Under the excitation of a confocal laser, the morphology of HeLa cells was not damaged and emitted bright red fluorescence (Fig. 6), indicating that AlCl3-CDs could smoothly cross the cell membrane and label HeLa cells, which also fully confirmed the potential of AlCl3-CDs as a fluorescent probe for live cell imaging.
